            "answer_text": "Calabrian Greek has some remarkable archaisms compared to Salento Greek, in vocabulary (a few Doricisms, some ancient particles), and in syntax (use of the participle as a verb complement: ste kulusa \u201cstands chasing\u201d = \u201cis chasing\u201d; survival of the infinitive after modals: sozzo milisi \u201ccan speak\u201d); see e.g. https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/0f4f/e2f129417f721ef9730d69f8dc60de328fe2.pdf But the guts of Calabrian Greek still looks like Standard Modern Greek. Maybe late Byzantine Greek, if you\u2019re interested in the infinitive survival; but linguistically we conventionally date Modern Greek from 1100 anyway. Modern Greek as spoken by the Mario Bros, admittedly: the intonation is Italian, and there is a lot of Italian vocabulary. Here\u2019s a sample of a Calabrian Greek-speaker, recounting his experience as a soldier in Greece during WWII: \u201cWhen I was a soldier, I ended up in Greece\u201d. That will be of use to Greek speakers and not non-Greek speakers, but Greek speakers will tell you it looks like what I say: Mario Bros Modern Greek, with some surprising archaisms\u2014but not enough archaisms to make it more Ancient Greek than Modern. Here\u2019s one para: Tutos ode, o greco, canni: \u00abMa eg\u00f2, san de cap\u00e8guo, ti en scero ec\u00ecno pu leghi, en scero, ec\u00ecno pu den mu leghi! Ti mu steki l\u00e8gonda?\u00bb San eg\u00f2 ec\u00e0pespa ec\u00ecno ti epl\u00e0tespe manach\u00f2stu, ce ipe ola tunda pr\u00e0mata, tu ipan eg\u00f2: \u00abScerise ti theli? Mian stampa al\u00e0di, enan pumad\u00f2ri, enan cromm\u00ecdi, na cami mian nzal\u00e0ta na fai, ti pin\u00e0i.\u00bb That man, the Greek, goes: \u201cBut me, if I can\u2019t understand him, I don\u2019t know what he is saying, and I don\u2019t know what he is not saying to me! What is he telling me?\u201d When I understood what he said on his own, and he said all that, I said to him: \u201cYou know what he wants? A little oil, a tomato, an onion, to make a salad to eat, because he is hungry.\u201d Archaisms: ode for \u201chere\u201d; steki l\u00e8gonda \u201cstands saying\u201d = \u201cis saying\u201d. Italian words italicised. Reactions from Greeks to the linked passage are welcome. ",
